<subSubSection id="91F4650B280EFFA7FF4CFC28FA9AFBAE" pageId="30" pageNumber="459" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="D9513680280EFFA7FF4CFC28FA9AFBAE" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="30" pageNumber="459">
<emphasis id="EB9AEA92280EFFA7FF4CFC28FE8BFB8A" bold="true" box="[199,334,1015,1041]" pageId="30" pageNumber="459">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a combination of two Greek terms: 
<emphasis id="EB9AEA92280EFFA7FC57FC28FBD1FB8A" box="[988,1044,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="459">lepto</emphasis>
(slender) and 
<emphasis id="EB9AEA92280EFFA7FB3FFC28FB2CFB8A" box="[1204,1257,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="459">styla</emphasis>
(pointed instrument), a reference to the elongate gonostylus which has a very long, slender outer prong, but, no inner prong.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
